---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const productSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Product",
  "name": "Nexrial CTMS vs Medrio — Comparison",
  "url": "https://purpledirective.com/nexrial-vs-medrio",
  "description": "An honest comparison of Nexrial CTMS and Medrio for clinical research sites and small site networks. Nexrial is a Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS) built for site operations; Medrio is primarily an Electronic Data Capture (EDC) platform with supplementary site-tracking features. The right choice depends on whether your primary need is site operations (CTMS) or sponsor-led data capture (EDC).",
  "brand": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Purple Directive"
  }
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is Nexrial or Medrio better for a clinical research site?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It depends on the primary job the site needs done. Nexrial is a Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS) built for site operations — regulatory binder, delegation log, visit scheduling, PI e-signatures, monitoring visit tracking, protocol deviations. Medrio is primarily an Electronic Data Capture (EDC) platform focused on sponsor-led data capture, eCOA (electronic Clinical Outcome Assessments), and randomization. For a site that needs to run its operations and satisfy monitors, Nexrial fits. For a site that needs to capture sponsor-required outcome data, Medrio (or another EDC) fits. Many sites use both categories of tool."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between CTMS and EDC?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS) is site operations software: subject tracking, visit scheduling, delegation log, regulatory binder, monitoring visit management, protocol deviations, billing, and 21 CFR Part 11 audit trail. An Electronic Data Capture (EDC) system is sponsor-facing data collection software: case report forms (CRFs), data queries, coding, study-level database locking, and sponsor reporting. A site running a sponsored trial typically uses both — the CTMS manages the site's own operations, and the EDC captures the data the sponsor requires. Nexrial is a CTMS. Medrio is primarily an EDC."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does Medrio cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Medrio's pricing is quote-based and not publicly listed as of April 2026. Industry reports place Medrio in the mid-market EDC range (ballpark $5,000 to $20,000 per year per study for site-facing deployments, higher for sponsor contracts), with volume-based pricing for CROs and sponsors. Medrio targets sponsor and CRO buyers more than independent sites. For current pricing, contact Medrio directly."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does Nexrial cost?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Nexrial is priced transparently: $349/month Core, $549/month Pro, and $199/month Founder tier for the first 5 sites. Pricing is per site, not per study. A small research site running 5-25 concurrent studies on a budget under $700/month fits the target profile. See https://nexrial.com for current pricing."
      }
    }
  ]
};

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://purpledirective.com/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Compare CTMS", "item": "https://purpledirective.com/best-ctms-small-clinical-sites" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Nexrial vs Medrio", "item": "https://purpledirective.com/nexrial-vs-medrio" }
  ]
};
---

<Base
  title="Nexrial vs Medrio — CTMS or EDC? Honest Comparison (April 2026)"
  activePage="products"
  description="Nexrial is a Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS) for site operations. Medrio is primarily an Electronic Data Capture (EDC) platform. They solve different problems. This page explains when to pick which — and why many sites run both."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(productSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />

  <div class="product-top">
    <div class="product-hero">
      <div class="product-hero-text">
        <span class="product-badge">CTMS vs EDC · Reviewed April 2026</span>
        <h1>Nexrial vs Medrio</h1>
        <p class="product-tagline">
          <strong>Short answer:</strong> Nexrial is a CTMS built for clinical research site
          operations. Medrio is primarily an EDC built for sponsor-led data capture. They
          are not direct competitors — they solve different problems. Many sites use both.
          This page explains when to pick which.
        </p>
        <a href="https://nexrial.com" class="buy-btn">Learn About Nexrial</a>
        <p class="buy-note">
          Reviewed <time datetime="2026-04-18">April 18, 2026</time> by
          Tyrian Murex, Purple Directive founder. Medrio pricing is quote-based and not
          publicly listed; ranges shown reflect industry reporting and should be verified
          with Medrio directly.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="product-hero-preview">
        <div>
          <p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; font-weight: 600; text-align: center;">At a glance</p>
          <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; font-size: 0.85rem; line-height: 1.8;">
            <li><strong>Nexrial:</strong> CTMS, $199–549/mo</li>
            <li><strong>Medrio:</strong> EDC-first, quote-based</li>
            <li>Different jobs to be done</li>
            <li>Common to use both</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>What each one actually is</h2>

    <h3>Nexrial — Clinical Trial Management System (CTMS)</h3>
    <p>
      Nexrial is site-operations software. Its job is to help a clinical research site
      run its studies: tracking subjects through visits, maintaining the regulatory
      binder, managing the delegation log, capturing PI e-signatures, scheduling
      monitoring visits, logging protocol deviations, and satisfying 21 CFR Part 11
      audit-trail requirements during sponsor monitoring and FDA inspection.
    </p>
    <p>
      Nexrial targets small independent sites and small site networks running 5–25
      concurrent studies on a budget under $700/month. Pricing is published:
      <strong>$349/month Core, $549/month Pro, $199/month Founder</strong> (first five sites).
    </p>

    <h3>Medrio — primarily Electronic Data Capture (EDC)</h3>
    <p>
      Medrio's core product is an Electronic Data Capture (EDC) platform: case report
      forms (CRFs), data queries, coding, randomization, and sponsor-facing data
      export. Medrio also offers eCOA (electronic Clinical Outcome Assessments), ePRO
      (electronic Patient Reported Outcomes), and eConsent. Medrio historically
      serves sponsors, CROs, and mid-size academic trials more than independent
      sites.
    </p>
    <p>
      Medrio pricing is quote-based and not publicly listed as of April 2026.
      Industry reports place it in the mid-market range — verify directly with
      Medrio for current numbers.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Feature-by-feature comparison</h2>
    <div class="compare-table-wrap">
      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Capability</th>
            <th scope="col">Nexrial (CTMS)</th>
            <th scope="col">Medrio (EDC-first)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Primary job</strong></td>
            <td>Site operations</td>
            <td>Sponsor-led data capture</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Subject tracking & visit scheduling</td>
            <td>✅ Native</td>
            <td>⚠️ Partial (limited CTMS features)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Regulatory binder (eTMF-adjacent)</td>
            <td>✅ Native</td>
            <td>❌ Not primary focus</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Delegation log</td>
            <td>✅ Native</td>
            <td>❌ Not a native feature</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Monitoring visit management</td>
            <td>✅ Native (SDV, findings, action items)</td>
            <td>❌ Not a native CTMS feature</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Case report forms (CRFs)</td>
            <td>⚠️ Basic; not a full EDC</td>
            <td>✅ Core product</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Data queries, coding, lock</td>
            <td>❌ Not in scope</td>
            <td>✅ Core product</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>eCOA / ePRO</td>
            <td>❌ Not in scope</td>
            <td>✅ Supported</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>eConsent</td>
            <td>⚠️ Consent version tracking; not full eConsent</td>
            <td>✅ Supported</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Randomization (IWRS)</td>
            <td>❌ Not in scope</td>
            <td>✅ Supported</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>21 CFR Part 11 audit trail</td>
            <td>✅ Database-level (3 independent defenses)</td>
            <td>✅ Validated</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>HIPAA BAA</td>
            <td>✅ Template ready; signed per tenant</td>
            <td>✅ Available</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>SOC 2 Type II</td>
            <td>⚠️ Readiness work begins at $10K ARR</td>
            <td>✅ Historically attested</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Pricing transparency</td>
            <td>✅ Published on website</td>
            <td>❌ Quote-based</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Target buyer</td>
            <td>Independent small sites; small site networks</td>
            <td>Sponsors; CROs; academic trials</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>When to pick which</h2>

    <h3>Pick Nexrial if…</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You run a small clinical research site (1–3 sites, 3–10 users) and need site-operations software</li>
      <li>Your studies are mostly sponsor-supplied with the sponsor's EDC already in place</li>
      <li>You need a regulatory binder, delegation log, and monitoring-visit workflow that monitors can audit</li>
      <li>Your budget is under $700/month and enterprise CTMS ($10K–100K/yr) isn't realistic</li>
      <li>You want published pricing and a vendor built by clinical research professionals</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Pick Medrio if…</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You need to capture CRF data from subjects — you're running investigator-initiated or sponsor-led trials and need your own EDC</li>
      <li>You need eCOA, ePRO, randomization, or full eConsent in one platform</li>
      <li>You are a sponsor or CRO (Medrio historically serves sponsor-side more than site-side)</li>
      <li>A mid-market EDC with validated data-capture + sponsor reporting is the primary need</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Use both if…</h3>
    <p>
      Your site runs a sponsored trial where the sponsor has specified Medrio (or another
      EDC) for data capture, and you also need your own CTMS for site operations, regulatory
      binder, and monitoring management. This is the common case for mid-size sites.
      Nexrial and Medrio do not overlap in the functions that matter most — they can sit
      side by side.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Pricing — honest table</h2>
    <div class="compare-table-wrap">
      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Plan</th>
            <th scope="col">Price</th>
            <th scope="col">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="compare-row-highlight">
            <td><strong>Nexrial Founder</strong></td>
            <td><strong>$199/month</strong></td>
            <td>First 5 sites only · full platform · published</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="compare-row-highlight">
            <td><strong>Nexrial Core</strong></td>
            <td><strong>$349/month</strong></td>
            <td>Up to 10 users · published</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="compare-row-highlight">
            <td><strong>Nexrial Pro</strong></td>
            <td><strong>$549/month</strong></td>
            <td>Up to 25 users · advanced audit + compliance reports · published</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Medrio — site tier</td>
            <td>Quote-based</td>
            <td>Industry reports: ~$5K–$20K/yr range · verify with Medrio</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Medrio — sponsor tier</td>
            <td>Quote-based</td>
            <td>Volume-based · multi-study contracts · verify with Medrio</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #64748b; margin-top: 1rem;">
      Medrio ranges are rough industry reporting, not Medrio's own published numbers.
      Contact Medrio directly for current pricing. Nexrial pricing is published on
      <a href="https://nexrial.com">nexrial.com</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>FAQ</h2>

    <h3>Can Nexrial replace Medrio for data capture?</h3>
    <p>
      No. Nexrial is not a full EDC. If you need CRF data capture, data queries, coding,
      and sponsor-facing database lock, you need an EDC — Medrio, Medidata Rave, Veeva
      Vault EDC, Castor, Clinical Studio, or similar. Nexrial does not compete in that
      category and does not claim to.
    </p>

    <h3>Can Medrio replace Nexrial for site operations?</h3>
    <p>
      Partially. Medrio has some site-tracking features, but the core workflows a small
      site needs — regulatory binder, delegation log, monitoring-visit management, PI
      e-signatures on site documents, protocol-deviation tracking separate from EDC
      queries — are not what Medrio is optimized for. A site could force-fit Medrio as
      a pseudo-CTMS, but it will feel heavy for the price.
    </p>

    <h3>Which integrates better with sponsor EDCs?</h3>
    <p>
      Sponsor EDCs are typically specified by the sponsor, not the site. Most sites
      log into whatever EDC the sponsor requires (Veeva Vault EDC, Medidata Rave,
      Medrio, Clinical Studio, Castor, etc.). A site-side CTMS like Nexrial stays
      out of that path — it tracks what the site owns (subjects, visits, regulatory
      binder, monitoring) without trying to be the data-capture layer.
    </p>

    <h3>Does Nexrial implement 21 CFR Part 11 controls?</h3>
    <p>
      Nexrial is designed against the controls of 21 CFR Part 11 Subpart B (electronic
      records). Audit-log integrity is protected by three independent database-level
      defenses (UPDATE, DELETE, and TRUNCATE all revoked), with validation package
      (VAL-PLAN, IQ/OQ/PQ, VAL-REPORT) and executed-run evidence available under NDA.
      Part 11 is a design standard, not a certification — see
      <a href="https://nexrial.com/trust">nexrial.com/trust</a> for live control posture.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="why-now-section">
    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <p>
      If you think Nexrial fits your site, email
      <a href="mailto:info@purpledirective.com">info@purpledirective.com</a> or
      book a demo at
      <a href="https://calendly.com/nexrial/demo" rel="noopener">calendly.com/nexrial/demo</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      If Medrio sounds like the better fit — meaning your primary need is EDC rather
      than site operations — contact Medrio directly at
      <a href="https://www.medrio.com" rel="noopener">medrio.com</a>. We don't have an
      affiliate relationship; we'd rather see sites in the right tool than in the
      wrong one.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
